To check the type of the values in Google Sheets, you can use JavaScript's `typeof` operator to determine the type of each cell's value. Google Sheets cells can contain different types of data: strings, numbers, booleans, dates, and errors. You can create a function to check for valid types and highlight cells that don't match the expected type.

Here's an example script that highlights cells with invalid types. In this example, we'll assume that valid types are numbers and booleans.

```javascript
function highlightBadValuesInWorkbook() {
  var spreadsheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet();
  var sheets = spreadsheet.getSheets();

  sheets.forEach(function(sheet) {
    var range = sheet.getDataRange();
    var values = range.getValues();

    for (var i = 0; i < values.length; i++) {
      for (var j = 0; j < values[i].length; j++) {
        var cellValue = values[i][j];
        if (!isValidValue(cellValue)) {
          var cell = range.getCell(i + 1, j + 1);
          cell.setBackground('red');
        }
      }
    }
  });
}

function isValidValue(value) {
  // Check the type of the value. Valid types are number and boolean.
  var type = typeof value;
  return type === 'number' || type === 'boolean';
}
```

### Additional Validations

If you want to add more types or specific checks, you can modify the `isValidValue` function accordingly.

#### Example for Checking Multiple Types

```javascript
function isValidValue(value) {
  var type = typeof value;
  // Check if the value is a number, boolean, or string (excluding empty strings)
  return (type === 'number' || type === 'boolean' || (type === 'string' && value !== ""));
}
```

#### Example for Checking Dates

If you want to include dates as valid values, you need to check if the value is a date object.

```javascript
function isValidValue(value) {
  var type = typeof value;
  // Check if the value is a number, boolean, or date object
  return type === 'number' || type === 'boolean' || (Object.prototype.toString.call(value) === '[object Date]' && !isNaN(value));
}
```

### How to Use the Script

